<subSubSection id="C31C65001974FFB36A8BA4707575FACE" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BB9368B1974FFB36A8BA47071E5FBA5" blockId="84.[189,457,1047,1073]" box="[189,457,1047,1073]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
<heading id="D0F181E71974FFB36A8BA47071E5FBA5" bold="true" box="[189,457,1047,1073]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B972EA991974FFB36A8BA47071E5FBA5" bold="true" box="[189,457,1047,1073]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Differential diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB9368B1974FFB36A8BA4217575FACE" blockId="84.[189,1399,1094,1370]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
<taxonomicName id="4C064D081974FFB36A8BA4217278FBF4" authority="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin, 2018" authorityName="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2018" box="[189,596,1094,1120]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigantea" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis id="B972EA991974FFB36A8BA4217278FBF4" box="[189,596,1094,1120]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Sphegina (Asiosphegina) gigantea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24157E21974FFB3686BA4217295FBF4" box="[605,697,1094,1120]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is similar to those other 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D081974FFB369D5A421747CFBF4" authorityName="Meigen" authorityYear="1822" box="[995,1104,1094,1120]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B972EA991974FFB369D5A421747CFBF4" box="[995,1104,1094,1120]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Sphegina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which have strong setae posteriorly on the male sternum IV, especially 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D081974FFB368C4A40C73A5FB10" authorityName="Hippa, van Steenis &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2015" box="[754,905,1129,1157]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigas" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis id="B972EA991974FFB368C4A40C73A5FB10" box="[754,905,1129,1157]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">S. (A.) gigas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D081974FFB369F1A40C7455FB10" authorityName="Hippa, van Steenis &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2015" box="[967,1145,1129,1157]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trispina" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis id="B972EA991974FFB369F1A40C7455FB10" box="[967,1145,1129,1157]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">S. (A.) trispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with which it shares the hyaline wing in combination with the presence of long sub-apical setae antero-dorsally on the hind femur. Except for the characters appearing in the key, it also differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D081974FFB36E3EA4D574BAFB5F" authorityName="Hippa, van Steenis &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2015" box="[1032,1174,1201,1228]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigas" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis id="B972EA991974FFB36E3EA4D574BAFB5F" box="[1032,1174,1201,1228]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">S. (A.) gigas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D081974FFB36EFAA4D5755AFB5F" authorityName="Hippa, van Steenis &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2015" box="[1228,1398,1201,1228]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trispina" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis id="B972EA991974FFB36EFAA4D5755AFB5F" box="[1228,1398,1201,1228]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">S. (A.) trispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having male sternum IV with a very narrow posterior submembranous flange (in 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D081974FFB36E99A4B1756FFB7B" authorityName="Hippa, van Steenis &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2015" box="[1199,1347,1237,1264]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigas" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis id="B972EA991974FFB36E99A4B1756FFB7B" box="[1199,1347,1237,1264]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">S. (A.) gigas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D081974FFB36A8BA49E7145FA87" authorityName="Hippa, van Steenis &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2015" box="[189,361,1272,1299]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trispina" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis id="B972EA991974FFB36A8BA49E7145FA87" box="[189,361,1272,1299]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">S. (A.) trispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
very wide). Sternum VII has a conical tubercle with long light pile as in 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D081974FFB36EF4A49E7543FA87" authorityName="Hippa, van Steenis &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2015" box="[1218,1391,1272,1299]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trispina" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis id="B972EA991974FFB36EF4A49E7543FA87" box="[1218,1391,1272,1299]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">S. (A.) trispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the pile is more seta-like; 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D081974FFB36811A57A7291FAA3" authorityName="Hippa, van Steenis &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2015" box="[551,701,1308,1335]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigas" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis id="B972EA991974FFB36811A57A7291FAA3" box="[551,701,1308,1335]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">S. (A.) gigas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a long finger-like process with long light yellow pile. Thus, the male genitalia of these three species are significantly different (see also 
<bibRefCitation id="EF974B7A1974FFB36E4AA5277561FACE" author="Hippa H. &amp; van Steenis J. &amp; Mutin V. A." box="[1148,1357,1344,1370]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="1 - 67" refId="ref91629" refString="Hippa H., van Steenis J. &amp; Mutin V. A. 2015. The genus Sphegina Meigen (Diptera, Syrphidae) in a biodiversity hotspot: the thirty-six sympatric species in Kambaiti, Myanmar. Zootaxa 3954 (1): 1 - 67. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3954.1.1" type="journal article" year="2015">
Hippa 
<emphasis id="B972EA991974FFB36EFDA526752AFACE" box="[1227,1286,1344,1370]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31C65001974FFB36A8BA5E57127FA7B" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BB9368B1974FFB36A8BA5E57168FA08" blockId="84.[189,324,1410,1436]" box="[189,324,1410,1436]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
